a Luiz Carlos Guedes) || 2001 || || || [[London]], [[England]]  \n|-\n|{{no2}}Loss|| Mark Robinson || Points || [[ADCC Submission Wrestling World Championship]] - Round of 16 (+99&nbsp;kg) || 2000 ||align=center| 1 ||align=center| 10:00 || [[Abu Dhabi, United Arab Emirates]] \n|-\n{{s-end}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20071025015907/http://www.ssjstudio.net/ Official website - SSJ Studio]\n*{{Sherdog}}\n*[http://www.prowrestlinghistory.com/ RINGS fight history]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hasdell, Lee}}\n[[Category:1966 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:English male mixed martial artists]]\n[[Category:Light heavyweight mixed martial artists]]\n[[Category:Heavyweight mixed martial artists]]\n[[Category:Mixed martial artists utilizing jujutsu]]\n[[Category:British jujutsuka]]\n[[Category:British male karateka]]\n[[Category:English male kickboxers]]\n[[Category:People from Milton Keynes]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Northampton]]\n", "text_old": "{{EngvarB|date=September 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2013}}\n{{short description|English kickboxer, combat sport promoter and mixed martial arts fighter}}\n{{Infobox martial artist\n| name            = Lee Hasdell\n| other_names     = Kagemusha<br /> Godfather of UK MMA<br /> The Gatekeeper\n| image           = Lee Hasdell.jpg\n| image_size      = 200px\n| alt             =\n| caption         =\n| birth_name      = Lee John Hasdell\n| birth_date      = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1966|12|13}}<ref name=\"sherdog\">[https://www.sherdog.com/fighter/Lee-Hasdell-1436]. Retrieved 4 April 2019</ref>\n| birth_place     = [[Northampton]], England\n| death_date      =\n| death_place     =\n| death_cause     =\n| residence       =\n| nationality     = British\n| height          = {{height|ft=6|in=1}}<ref name=\"sherdog\"/>\n| weight_lb       = \n| weight_class    = {{plainlist|<small>\n*[[Kickboxing weight classes|Super-Welterweight]] (1989)\n*[[Kickboxing weight classes|Middleweight]] (1989-1990)\n*[[Kickboxing weight classes|Super Middleweight]] (1990-1991)\n*[[Kickboxing weight classes|Light-Heavyweight]] (1991-1993)\n*[[Kickboxing weight classes|Super Light-Heavyweight]] (1993-1994)\n*[[Kickboxing weight classes|Cruiserweight]] (1994)\n*[[Kickboxing weight classes|Super Cruiserweight]] (1994-1995)\n*[[Kickboxing weight classes|Heavyweight]] (1995)\n*[[Kickboxing weight classes|Super Heavyweight]] (1995-2002)\n*(''Kickboxing'')\n*[[Heavyweight (MMA)|Heavyweight]]/Open-weight (1995-2001)\n*[[Light Heavyweight (MMA)|Light-Heavyweight]] (2004-2007)\n*(''Mixed martial arts'')\n</small>}}\n| reach           =\n| style           = Shin Senjutsu\n| stance          = \n| team            = SSJ\n| fighting_out_of = [[Milton Keynes]], England\n| rank            = {{colorbox|black}} 7th Dan Black Belt in [[Kickboxing]]<br />{{colorbox|black}} 7th Dan Black Belt in [[Karate]]<br />{{colorbox|black}} 2nd Dan Black Belt in [[K\u016bd\u014d|Kudo Daido Juku]]<br />{{colorbox|black}} Black Belt in [[Ju-jitsu]]<br/>{{colorbox|black}} Black Belt in Submission Arts Wrestling<ref>{{cite web|url=https://submissionwrestlingarts.com/saw/saw-black-belts|title=Submission Arts Wrestling Black Belts|publisher=World Submission Wrestling Federation|accessdate=April 11, 2016}}</ref>\n| years_active    = 1989-2007\n| kickbox_win     = 40\n| kickbox_kowin   = 26\n| kickbox_loss    = 17\n| kickbox_koloss  =\n| kickbox_draw    = \n| kickbox_nc      =\n| mma_kowin       = 9\n| mma_subwin      = 5\n| mma_decwin      = 1\n| mma_dqwin       = 1\n| mma_koloss      = 4\n| mma_subloss     = 7\n| mma_decloss     = 5\n| mma_draw        = 3\n| mma_nc          = 1\n| occupation      =\n| university      =\n| spouse          =\n| relatives       =\n| Children        =\n| club            = \n| school          =\n| url             = {{URL|http://www.ssjstudio.net/}}\n| boxrec          =\n| sherdog         = 1436\n| footnotes       =\n| updated         = 28 March 2020}}\n\n'''Lee Hasdell''' (born 13 December 1966)<ref name=\"k1sport\">[http://k-1sport.de/en/database/show_fighter.php?id=507 K-1Sport.de fighter profile]. Retrieved 4 January 2009.</ref> is a [[United Kingdom|British]] [[martial artist]], [[promoter (entertainment)|promoter]] and former professional [[kickboxer]] and [[Mixed martial arts|mixed martial artist]]. Hasdell is considered by many to be a pioneer of mixed martial arts in the [[United Kingdom]], particularly in the 1990s, when he drove a great deal of innovation in the field.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|url=http://www.iska.org.uk/news/article/iska_uk_launch_mma_division_headed_by_lee_hasdell/|title=ISKA UK Launch MMA Division headed by Lee Hasdell|author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.-->|first=|date=18 March 2009|website=ISKA|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303224050/http://www.iska.org.uk/news/article/iska_uk_launch_mma_division_headed_by_lee_hasdell/|archivedate=3 March 2016|access-date=13 August 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Hasdell promoted the first professional mixed martial arts events in the UK<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.sherdog.com/news/articles/Anarchy-in-the-UK-34824|title=Anarchy in the U.K.|author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date= 22 August 2011|website=www.sherdog.com|publisher= |access-date=3 April 2019 |quote=The first true U.K. MMA shows were the Night of the Samurai events staged by Lee Hasdell in the late 1990s.}}</ref><ref name=\"Lewis 45\">{{cite magazine |last=Lewis |first=Peter |date=April 2004 |title=A Total Fighter \u2013 An interview with Lee Hasdell |magazine=Fighters |location= |publisher=Tim Ayling |page=45 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=p5ioCwAAQBAJ&pg=PT28&lpg=PT28&dq=john+kavanagh+godfather+lee+hasdell&source=bl&ots=DEyt1omNw0&sig=qy4MS0A9yMLCOfhO8zrFtHLv44w&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjZ0c-wjNDOAhXoD8AKHbF-Dz8Q6AEIHDAA#v=onepage&q=john%20kavanagh%20godfather%20lee%20hasdell&f=false |title=Win or Learn: MMA, Conor McGregor and Me: A Trainer's Journey |author= John Kavanagh |date= 30 June 2016 |website= |publisher=Penguin |access-date=20 August 2016 |quote= \"and promoted the first events in the UK, so he's regarded as the Godfather of UK MMA\".}}</ref> and helped develop many of the standards within the British MMA scene of today.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nHasdell began his professional career in 1989, as a [[Muay Thai]] boxer; becoming a three-time British champion in kickboxing and Thai boxing.<ref name=\"Lewis 46\">{{cite magazine |last=Lewis |first=Peter |date=April 2004 |title=A Total Fighter \u2013 An interview with Lee Hasdell |magazine=Fighters |location= |publisher=Tim Ayling |page=46 }}</ref>  In 1995, he became one of the first British fighters to compete in [[K-1]].<ref name=\":0\" /> Around this time, Hasdell began crossing over into mixed martial arts as a [[shootfighter]] and later made his official debut for Rings [[Holland]] in 1996. Shortly afterwards he won the inaugural world [[Oktagon]] challenge in [[Milan, Italy]].<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\"Lewis 52\">{{cite magazine |last=Lewis |first=Peter |date=April 2004 |title=A Total Fighter \u2013 An interview with Lee Hasdell |magazine=Fighters |location= |publisher=Tim Ayling |page=52 }}</ref> In 1997, he made his debut for [[Fighting Network RINGS]] in [[Japan]] and would go on to have the majority of his fights there until 2001. \n\nThroughout his mixed martial arts career, Lee Hasdell fought 22-times for Rings in Japan, Holland and [[Russia]] as well as on his own promotion Total Fight Forum (TFF), which was in conjunction with Rings. He would also compete at the [[ADCC Submission Wrestling World Championship]] and IAFC - Absolute Fighting Championships in 2000. His final mixed martial arts bout was in 2007 on the UK promotion [[Cage Rage]]. Hasdell's professional career spanned nearly 19 years with almost 100 bouts in kickboxing and mixed martial arts.\n\n==Martial arts background==\n\nLee Hasdell began martial arts in 1979 at the age of 12, learning [[Taekwondo]] under Morris Young who was the European full-contact taekwondo heavyweight champion. Lee Later took up [[boxing]] and then [[karate]] as he felt that it was more of a mixed style that suited his stand up. After winning a number of local tournaments he decided to study full-contact Karate. In 1985 when he was 18 he started weight training and kickboxing. In 1987 he moved to [[Milton Keynes]] from [[Northampton]] where he began [[Thai boxing]]. Hasdell was taught by Brian Walker who was one of [[Master Toddy]]'s first generation instructors and would train under him until 1992.<ref>{{cite magazine |last=Clifton |first=Paul |date=August 1999 |title=Lee Hasdell Rules The Ring! |page=12 |magazine=Combat Magazine |volume=25 |issue=5 |location= |publisher= }}</ref><ref name=\"Lewis 45\"/>\n\n==Kickboxing (1989\u20132002)==\n\n===Domestic career (1989\u20131993)===\nHasdell began his professional [[kickboxing]] career in January 1989 at the age of 22 as a [[Kickboxing weight classes|super-welterweight]] Thai boxer. In 1991, Lee went over to train at the Gym International and the [[Chakuriki Gym]] in [[Amsterdam, Netherlands]], this is where Lee was first introduced to Japanese Kickboxing and Kyokushin methods.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.15909.mrsite.com/page3.htm |title=SSJ Origins |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date= |website=KTMMA |publisher= |access-date=13 August 2016 |quote=In 1991, Lee went over to train at the Gym International and the Chakuriki Gym in Amsterdam, Netherlands, this is where Lee was first introduced to Japanese Kickboxing and Kyokushin methods.}}</ref> On 9 March 1991, Hasdell won the [[World Kickboxing Association|WKA]] British [[kickboxing weight classes|super-middleweight]] kickboxing title. The next month he moved up to [[Kickboxing weight classes|light-heavyweight]] and won the BIKA British Thai boxing title. He later added the BIKA British light-heavyweight free-style title in 1992.<ref name=\"Lewis 46\"/> Hasdell remained undefeated as British champion for two years.<ref>{{cite news |first= |last= |coauthors= |title=Lee's Title Chance |work=Milton Keynes Citizen |page= |date=May 1993 |quote= }}</ref>\n\n===International career (1993\u20131995)===\nHasdell's quest for the European title began on 28 May 1993 in [[Katowice]], [[Poland]]. He fought Paval Rumas for the [[ISKA]] European light-heavyweight full-contact title and lost by split decision after 10 rounds. Hasdell later moved up to [[Kickboxing weight classes|super light-heavyweight]] and challenged for both the [[World Kickboxing Association|WKA]] [[Commonwealth of Nations|Commonwealth]] and [[Europe]]an [[Muay Thai]] titles. He lost the first title fight against [[Duncan Airlie James]] due to a cut in October 1993. This bout was only one week removed from originally receiving the cut in a Thai boxing match in [[Arnhem]], [[Netherlands]] against Perry Telgt. Still ranked no.1 in Britain,<ref name=\"WKA Announcements 1994 62-65\">{{Citation |last=Lane|first=Stuart |title=World Kick Boxing Association Championships|newspaper=WKA Advertisement |pages=62\u201365 |date=January 1994 }}</ref>  Hasdell fought for the European title on 22 January 1994 against [[Bob Schrijber]] at the [[Olympic Stadium (Moscow arena)|Olympic Stadium]] in [[Moscow]], [[Russia]]. Hasdell was stopped near the end of the last round due to leg kicks.<ref name=totalfighter>{{Citation |last=Lewis |first=Peter |title=A Total Fighter |newspaper=Fighters \u2013 Kickboxing News |pages=45\u201347 |date=April 2004 }}</ref><ref name=\"WKA Announcements 1994 62-65\" /> \n\nIn April 1994, Hasdell trained at the [[Seidokaikan]] Dojo in Japan, the headquarters for the [[K-1]] organisation.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ssjstudio.net/page4.htm |title=SSJ Origins |publisher=SSJ Dojo |accessdate=27 September 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111004224057/http://www.ssjstudio.net/page4.htm |archivedate=4 October 2011 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> He also attended the [[List of K-1 events|K-1 Grand Prix '94]] as a stand by fighter. On 17 October 1994, Hasdell made a move to [[Kickboxing weight classes|super-cruiserweight]] when he defeated [[France|French]] fighter Bruno Fariot by first round knock-out. He later returned to train at the [[Chakuriki Gym]] to prepare for his future fights<ref name=\"The Kickboxing Showdown\">{{Citation |last=Promotions|first=Roundhouse |title=Lee Hasdell is flying high with the Milton Keynes Fight Centre |newspaper= The Kickboxing Showdown - Title Fights |page=2 |date=November 1994 }}</ref> and was ranked no.1 in the Commonwealth ratings.<ref>{{Citation |last= |first= |title=The Night of Truth |page=107 |newspaper=Combat Magazine |volume=20 |issue=11 |date=November 1994 }}</ref> On 15 April 1995, Hasdell fought undefeated American fighter [[Curtis Schuster]] for the [[ISKA]] [[world]] [[Kickboxing weight classes|super-heavyweight]] [[Muay Thai]] title in [[Paris, France]]. Hasdell lost in the first round via a knee strike.<ref>[http://www.ikfkickboxing.com/CurtisSchuster.htm]. Retrieved 28 March 2013.</ref><ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=GfN9hx1-2zw]. Retrieved 21 May 2015.</ref> \n\nOn 3 September 1995, he became one of the first British fighters to compete in K-1 when he fought [[South Africa]]n Duane Van Der Merwe at [[K-1 Revenge II]] in [[Yokohama]], Japan.<ref name=\"iska\">{{cite web |url=http://www.iska.org.uk/news/article/iska_uk_launch_mma_division_headed_by_lee_hasdell/ |title=ISKA UK Launch MMA division headed by Lee Hasdell |publisher=International Sport Kickboxing Association |accessdate=27 September 2001 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303224050/http://www.iska.org.uk/news/article/iska_uk_launch_mma_division_headed_by_lee_hasdell/ |archivedate=3 March 2016 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Hasdell, who was significantly smaller than his opponent, lost in the first round by clinch knees. K-1 since banned unlimited strikes while in the clinch.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.headkicklegend.com/2010/3/27/1392947/k-1-rule-change-strikes-from-the |title=K-1 Rule change |publisher=Fraser Coffeen |accessdate=27 December 2011 }}</ref> After this fight and at the age of 28, Hasdell put his kickboxing career on hold to concentrate on [[shootfighting]], leaving behind a kickboxing record of 39 wins (25 T/KO) with 15 losses.<ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=oT_uYFyjIBA] kickboxing record announced in Italiano (Translated \u2013 Competition record \u2013 56 fights, 40 wins (26KO, 14 Dec), 15 losses and 1 draw) subtract pre-20 April 1996 MMA record (1W(1 T/KO)-0L-1D). Retrieved 4 April 2011.</ref>\n\n===Kickboxing returns===\nOn 13 December 1997, Lee Hasdell made a brief return to [[kickboxing]] when he entered an 8-man tournament in [[Prague]], [[Czech Republic]]. He took on [[Mirko Filipovic]] in the quarter-finals and was defeated by TKO (cut) in round 2. \n\nOn 16 April 2000, Hasdell made another kickboxing comeback at [[K-1 UK Battle of Britain 2000]] held in [[Birmingham]], England. This was the first K-1 event to be held in the [[United Kingdom]]. Hasdell defeated world heavyweight kickboxing champion [[Simon Dore]] by KO (flying knee) at 0:30 of round 3.<ref>{{cite magazine |last=Clifton |first=Paul |date=October 2000 |title=K-1 Battle of Britain |page=108 |magazine=Combat Magazine |volume=26 |issue=10 |location= |publisher= }}</ref>\n\nShortly after competing in his final mixed martial arts bout in Japan, Hasdell competed in a [[shootboxing]] match on 2 February 2002 in Tokyo, Japan against French fighter [[Cyrille Diabate]]. Hasdell lost by TKO due to referee stoppage at 2:18 of round 4.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.boutreview.com/news/data/striking/1012579602.html |title= \u30b7\u30e5\u30fc\u30c8\u30dc\u30af\u30b7\u30f3\u30b0 The age of \"S\" vol.1 2002\u5e742\u67081\u65e5(\u91d1)\u3000\u6771\u4eac\u30fb\u5f8c\u697d\u5712\u30db\u30fc\u30eb |last= |first= |date= |access-date=16 August 2016 |language=Japanese |trans-title=Shoot Boxing The age of S, Volume 1. February 1, 2002 (gold) Tokyo Korakuen Hall}}</ref><ref>[http://www.mixedmartialarts.com/events/Shoot-Boxing--S-Volume-1:AB741964-D512-4D9C-A4A5-818B9075BBE5]. Retrieved 16 August 2016.</ref>\n\n==Mixed martial arts career (1995\u20132007)==\n\n===Background===\nIn 1992, while teaching kickboxing at a Japanese Boarding School, Lee Hasdell began cross training with the Japanese martial arts instructors in [[Judo]], [[Karate]] and [[Jujitsu]].<ref>name=ktmma>{{cite web |url=http://www.ktmma.com/lee-hasdell.php/|title=An interview with MMA Legend Lee Hasdell |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date= |website=KTMMA |publisher= |access-date=16 August 2016 |quote=I was practicing MMA in 1992 by default as I was teaching Kickboxing at a Japanese boarding school and some of the in house Japanese martial arts instructors where teaching Judo, Karate and Jujitsu etc.}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine |last=Clifton |first=Paul |date=August 1999 |title=Lee Hasdell Rules The Ring! |page=14 |magazine=Combat Magazine |volume=25 |issue=8 |location= |publisher= }}</ref> Hasdell would later witness a match under [[mixed martial arts]] rules while as a stand-by fighter for [[K-1]] in April 1994. In September 1995 when he fought at [[K-1 Revenge II]] in Japan, Hasdell shared a dressing room with the mixed martial artists that were competing that night. They had [[Vale Tudo]] and [[shootfighting]] bouts on the card, which Hasdell watched with interest<ref>{{cite magazine |last=Lewis |first=Peter |date=April 2004 |title=A Total Fighter \u2013 An interview with Lee Hasdell |magazine=Fighters |location= |publisher=Tim Ayling |page=49 }}</ref> and when he returned from Japan, he began grappling.<ref>{{cite magazine |last=Clifton |first=Paul |date=August 1999 |title=Lee Hasdell Rules The Ring! |pages=12\u201314 |magazine=Combat Magazine |volume=25 |issue=8 |location= |publisher= }}</ref>\n\n===Early career (1995-1997)===\nOn 15 October 1995, Hasdell promoted a kickboxing event in [[Milton Keynes]], England which featured three shootfighting contests. The main attraction was a match between Lee Hasdell and [[United States|American]] freestyle [[wrestler]] Boston Jones. The fight was billed as \"The first ultimate shootfight in Britain\". Hasdell won the fight by technical-knockout due to a cut from a Knee in round 2.<ref name=\"Richmond\">{{Citation |last=Richmond |first=Tom |title=Entertainment for the Family? |newspaper=Milton Keynes Citizen |date=October 1995}}</ref><ref name=\"groups.google.com\">{{cite web |url=https://groups.google.com/forum/?fromgroups=#!topic/rec.martial-arts/3Je7pU4hhiM  |accessdate=2013-03-29 |df=dmy-all}}. Retrieved 29 March 2013.</ref> On 18 February 1996 at the age of 29, Lee Hasdell made his shootfighting debut for Rings Holland at Kings of Martial Arts against [[Netherlands|Dutch]] Thai boxer and multiple time world champion [[Andre Mannaart]]. Although the fight ended in a draw, it brought Hasdell to the attention of [[Akira Maeda]], the president of [[Fighting Network Rings|Fighting Network RINGS]]. \n\nOn 20 April 1996, Hasdell entered the world [[Oktagon]] challenge, an eight-man tournament held in  [[Milan]], [[Italy]]. The tournament featured fighters from the [[United States]], [[Israel]], [[Spain]], [[Netherlands]], [[Nigeria]], [[France]] and Italy, all representing eight different martial arts, with Hasdell represented the UK and the art of free-style fighting. The event was attended by 14,000 spectators.<ref>{{cite magazine |last=Lewis |first=Peter |date=April 2004 |title=A Total Fighter \u2013 An interview with Lee Hasdell |magazine=Fighters \u2013 The martial arts magazine |location= |publisher=Tim Ayling |page=52}}</ref> The rules of the tournament were similar to [[shootboxing]] but with grappling and submissions on the ground; wearing ten ounce gloves with thirty seconds of ground fighting.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.grappling-italia.com/news/2016/03/31/catch-wrestling-paolo-pillot-42035.html |title=Catch Wrestling & Grappling per le MMA: la visione di PAOLO PILLOT|last= |first= |date= 31 March 2016|access-date=19 March 2019 |language=Italian |trans-title=Catch Wrestling & Grappling for MMA: the vision of PAOLO PILLOT}}</ref> At the time it was considered 'free-fighting', a name that originally referred to [[mixed martial arts]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bellator.com/articles/eacmez/several-competitors-announced-for-bellator-oktagon-co-promotion-in-torino-on-april-16|title=Several competitors announced for Bellator - Oktagon co-promotion in Torino on April 16|author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date= 18 March 2019|website=www.bellator.com|publisher= |access-date=18 March 2018 |quote=At its beginning the show was dedicated to free fight, the name that was given initially to MMA (Mixed Martial Arts). }}</ref> Hasdell went through to the final with two knockouts over American [[Jeet Kun Do]] practitioner Scott Dobbs and Italian [[Judo]] and [[Karate]] champion Paolo Di Clemente. In the final he defeated [[Andre Mannaart]] by decision to become the new world Oktagon champion.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.iska.org.uk/news/article/iska_uk_launch_mma_division_headed_by_lee_hasdell/ |title=ISKA UK Launch MMA Division headed by Lee Hasdell |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=18 March 2009 |website=ISKA |access-date=15 August 2016 |quote=he had shocked the world by winning an eight man Shootboxing Tournament in Milan beating Dutch Kickboxing star Andre Manaart in the final. |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303224050/http://www.iska.org.uk/news/article/iska_uk_launch_mma_division_headed_by_lee_hasdell/ |archivedate=3 March 2016 |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref name=\"Milton Keynes Citizen \">{{Citation |last=Chapman |first=Paul |title=Champion Lee is a Prize Guy |newspaper=Citizen |page= |date=April 1996 }}</ref>\n\nFollowing his Oktagon victory, Hasdell was invited to train at the Rings [[Dojo]] in [[Yokohama]], Japan for four weeks.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.iska.org.uk/news/article/iska_uk_launch_mma_division_headed_by_lee_hasdell/ |title=ISKA UK Launch MMA Division headed by Lee Hasdell |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=18 March 2009 |website=ISKA |access-date=15 August 2016 |quote=start training in MMA with famous Japanese wrestler Akira Meada at the RINGS Dojo, shortly after he had shocked the world by winning an eight man Shootboxing Tournament in Milan. |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303224050/http://www.iska.org.uk/news/article/iska_uk_launch_mma_division_headed_by_lee_hasdell/ |archivedate=3 March 2016 |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine |last=Lewis |first=Peter |date=April 2004 |title=A Total Fighter \u2013 An interview with Lee Hasdell |magazine=Fighters \u2013 The martial arts magazine |location= |publisher=Tim Ayling |page=54 }}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine |last=Clifton |first=Paul |date=August 1999 |title=Lee Hasdell Rules The Ring! |page=14 |magazine=Combat Magazine |volume=25 |issue=5 |location= |publisher= }}</ref> Upon his return he began staging unofficial invitational matches in preparation for his future events<ref name=\"Lewis 52\"/> and competed in mixed rules matches throughout the year. On 26 October 1996, Hasdell fought Cees Bezems in a no holds barred match at IMA - Battle of Styles held in [[Amsterdam]], [[Netherlands]]. Hasdell lost by technical-knockout due to a cut.\n\n===Shootfighting in Japan, Holland and UK (1997-1999)===\nOn 2 February 1997, Hasdell made his second appearance for Rings Holland; now with [[Akira Maeda]] in his corner, fought Rings veteran [[Hans Nijman]] in Amsterdam, Netherlands. This bout ended up having a controversial finish. In the second round Nijman had Hasdell in a [[guillotine choke]], Hasdell grabbed the ropes for a rope escape although the referee did not see it, forcing Hasdell to tap out to break the hold.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://s94991397.onlinehome.us/newsite/tapes0001-0999/tape0549.htm |title=Tape 549 \u2013 Rings 2/2/97 |accessdate=27 December 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120301154817/http://s94991397.onlinehome.us/newsite/tapes0001-0999/tape0549.htm |archivedate=1 March 2012 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> On 4 April 1997, Hasdell made his debut for Fighting Network RINGS in [[Tokyo]], Japan. He defeated American Sean McCully by guillotine choke at 3:59. Hasdell returned to Tokyo two months later to compete in the Rings [[light-heavyweight]] tournament for the divisions inaugural title and lost to [[Masayuki Naruse]] in the quarter-finals by submission.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.prowrestlinghistory.com/shoot/rings/ringstitletny.html#light |title=Light Heavyweight Title Tournament 1997 |publisher=ProWrestlingHistory.com |accessdate=27 December 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bekkoame.ne.jp/~bryann/ariake/dai2.html|title=\u7b2c\u4e8c\u8a66\u5408\u300030\u5206\u4e00\u672c\u52dd\u8ca0 |last= |first= |date= |access-date=16 August 2016 |language=Japanese |trans-title=The second game 30 minutes one-game match}}</ref> \n\nOn 5 October 1997, Hasdell promoted his first official mixed martial arts event; the first in the [[United Kingdom]], called Total Fight Night. He would also feature on the card and defeated Dutch karate champion Peter Dijkman by rear naked choke, winning the vacant U.T.F super-fight heavyweight shootfighting title.<ref name=\"lwf-network1997\">{{cite web |url=http://www.lwf-network.com/?page_id=126 |title=RINGS TOTAL FIGHT NIGHT 1997.10.05 \u30df\u30eb\u30c8\u30f3\u30ad\u30fc\u30f3\u30ba\u3001\u30b5\u30f3\u30af\u30c1\u30e5\u30a2\u30ea\u30fb\u30a2\u30ea\u30fc\u30ca|last= |first= |date= |access-date=15 August 2016 |language=Japanese |trans-title=RINGS TOTAL FIGHT NIGHT 1997.10.05 Milton Keynes, Sanctuary Arena}}</ref> Later that same month, Hasdell competed in the annual RINGS: Mega Battle Tournament, a 16-man tournament to determine the first ever Rings open-weight champion. In the round of 16, He lost to [[Joop Kasteel]] by submission.<ref name=\"mega battle 1997\">[http://www.prowrestlinghistory.com/shoot/rings/ringsmega.html]. Retrieved 31 March 2016.</ref> \n\nOn 7 March 1998 at Hasdell's second mixed martial arts event Night of the Samurai, he fought Dutch fighter [[Sander Thonhauser]] in a [[Vale Tudo]] match, winning by [[armbar]] at just 55 seconds of round 1 to win the vacant U.T.F super-fight heavyweight Vale Tudo title. On 29 May 1998, Hasdell fought [[Hiromitsu Kanehara]] in [[Sapporo]], Japan. The match went the full thirty minutes and Kanehara was declared the winner due to multiple forced rope escapes. Just over a week later in [[Utrecht]], Netherlands he beat Dutch fighter [[Dave van der Veen]] by knock-out in the second round, securing his first victory in Rings Holland. On 21 September 1998, Hasdell returned to Japan where he defeated [[Kenichi Yamamoto (fighter)|Kenichi Yamamoto]] by KO.<ref name=\"KYamamoto\">{{cite web |url=http://www.prowrestlinghistory.com/shoot/rings/rings1998.html#092198 |title=Fighting Network Rings Cards 1998 |publisher=ProWrestlingHistory.com |accessdate=28 September 2011}}</ref> On 11 October 1998, Hasdell re-matched [[Hiromitsu Kanehara]], this time at Night of the Samurai II in [[Milton Keynes]], England. After 15 minutes, Hasdell lost again by decision. Later that month, he fought [[Gilbert Yvel]] in [[Heerenveen]], Netherlands and was defeated via technical-knockout due to a cut in the first round.\n\nOn 20 November 1998, Hasdell began what would be a trilogy of matches with [[Yasuhito Namekawa]]. Their first confrontation was held in [[Osaka]], Japan; after twenty minutes it was declared a draw.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.boutreview.com/total/rings/981120r/981120r1.html|title=\u7b2c\uff11\u8a66\u5408\uff0820\u5206\uff11\u672c\u52dd\u8ca0\uff09|last= |first= |date= |access-date=4 April 2019|language=Japanese |trans-title=The first game (one 20 minutes match) }}</ref><ref name=\"Clifton 1999 15\">{{Citation |last=Clifton |first=Paul |title=Lee Hasdell Rules The Ring! |newspaper=Combat |page=15 |date=August 1999}}</ref> Their rematch was held on 23 January 1999 at the [[Budokan Hall]] in Tokyo, Japan. Hasdell received a yellow card for an illegal punch and failed to finish Namekawa off after landing multiple knee strikes, losing the contest by decision.<ref name=\"RINGS 1999\">{{cite web |url=http://www.prowrestlinghistory.com/shoot/rings/rings1999.html |title=Fighting Network Rings Cards 1999 |publisher=ProWrestlingHistory.com |accessdate=21 May 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"Clifton 1999 15\"/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.boutreview.com/total/rings/990123r/990123r1.html|title=\u7b2c\uff11\u8a66\u5408\uff0820\u5206\uff11\u672c\u52dd\u8ca0\uff09  |last= |first= |date= |access-date=4 April 2019|language=Japanese |trans-title=The first game (one 20 minutes match)}}</ref> The third and final bout was held in Milton Keynes, England at Night of the Samurai III on 7 March 1999. Hasdell was trailing the fight by two points before knocking Namekawa out with a knee strike at 5:55. \n\nHe returned to Japan on 23 April 1999, defeating [[Ryuki Ueyama]] due to disqualification and submitting [[Ricardo Fyeet]] four months later. On 15 September 1999, Hasdell fought [[Satoshi Honma]] in Tokyo, Japan. After twenty minutes, the bout ended in a draw. The following month, Hasdell faced [[Dave van der Veen]] for a second time at Total Fight KRG 5 in Milton Keynes, England. Hasdell won by [[armbar]] at 1:47 of the first round to retain his U.T.F super-fight heavyweight shootfighting title.\n\n===Rings King of Kings, injuries and hiatuses (1999-2001)===\nOn 28 October 1999, Hasdell competed in the [[RINGS King of Kings Tournament 1999]], in the round of 32 he defeated [[Achmed Labasanov]] by TKO in round 2. Hasdell was eliminated in the following round by Brazilian fighter, [[Renato Sobral]] by unanimous decision. Hasdell became the first British fighter to compete in a major international mixed martial arts tournament. This was the first event in Rings to introduce the King of Kings rules with Vale Tudo gloves, rounds and judges.<ref>[http://www.bloodyelbow.com/2011/7/28/2297846/strikeforce-fedor-vs-henderson-dan-hendersons-run-through-rings-king-of-kings-1999]. Retrieved 16 August 2016.</ref> Hasdell took a break after this tournament to heal an injured knee.<ref>{{cite magazine |last=Clifton |first=Paul |date=July 2000 |title=Lee Hasdell \u2013 Fighting Back! |page=12 |magazine=Combat Magazine |volume=26 |issue=7 |location= |publisher= }}</ref>\n\nAfter a six-month break, Hasdell returned to mixed martial arts when he travelled to [[Moscow, Russia]] on 29 April 2000 to compete in the IAFC - Absolute Fighting Championships. In the first round, Hasdell lost to IAFC champion and eventual winner of the tournament Mikhail Avetisyan due to ground and pound. On 20 May 2000, he returned to Russia where he fought [[Mikhail Illoukhine]] at Rings Russia - Russia vs. the World, losing by split decision. Two weeks later Hasdell re-matched [[Joop Kasteel]], this time in the [[Netherlands]]. Hasdell lost the fight due to a [[dislocated shoulder]] in the opening round after knocking Kasteel down twice early in the match. \n\nHe returned six months later on 22 December 2000 and took on Rings veteran [[Volk Han]] in the round of 32 of the annual King of Kings tournament. Hasdell lost by TKO in the second round after he suffered an eye injury from one of the punches. On 28 January 2001, Hasdell returned to the Netherlands to fight [[Sander Thonhauser]] for a second time. During the bout, Thonhauser kneed Hasdell clean in the face while Hasdell was still on the floor, which is an illegal move; following a retaliation by Hasdell, the match was declared a [[No contest (boxing)|no contest]] in the opening round.\n\nHasdell was then scheduled to face British fighter James Zikic on 11 March 2001 at Millennium Brawl 2 but pulled out due to an eye injury he received in training. Hasdell took most of the year off and during this time Hasdell appeared in a music video for American singer [[Shea Seger]] in April 2001. In August, Hasdell was given an award from [[Akira Maeda]] in Japan for his hard work, dedication and contribution to the martial arts worldwide.<ref>[http://www.15909.mrsite.com/page3.htm]. Retrieved 9 August 2016.</ref>\n\n====Rings World Title Series 2001====\nNine months after his last fight, Hasdell returned to compete in the Absolute Class Tournament at Rings World Title Series on 20 October 2001. In the quarter-finals he beat [[Bulgaria]]n Judo player [[Georgi Tonkov]] by flying knee in round 1.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.prowrestlinghistory.com/|title=Pro Wrestling History|website=www.prowrestlinghistory.com}}</ref> On 21 December 2001, in the semi-final of the tournament, Hasdell lost to [[Fedor Emelianenko]] by [[guillotine choke]] in the first round. This was the first time since 25 October 1997 that Hasdell had submitted due to a submission hold, a total of over four years and 23 bouts (including submission grappling). At the age of 35, Lee Hasdell finished his 6 year career with Rings as the promotion would cease operating from 2002.\n\n===Post Rings===\nLee Hasdell resumed his mixed martial arts career on 24 April 2004 at Pain and Glory, held at the [[National Exhibition Centre|NEC]] in Birmingham, England. Now fighting at 92&nbsp;kg, around 10&nbsp;kg lighter than his fighting weight in Rings, he defeated Japanese fighter [[Fighting Network RINGS|Hiroyuki Ito]] by knock-out at 0:32 of round 1.\n\nAt the age of 40, after a 3-year hiatus from the sport, Hasdell made his [[Cage Rage]] debut at [[2007 in Cage Rage Championships|Cage Rage 22]] on 14 July 2007 at [[Wembley Arena]] in [[London]]. He fought Brazilian [[Mario Sperry]] in the [[light heavyweight (MMA)|light-heavyweight]] division and lost by [[rear naked choke]] in the first round. On 1 December 2007, Hasdell fought Italian Ivan Serati at [[2007 in Cage Rage Championships|Cage Rage 24]]. Hasdell lost again by rear naked choke at 1:34 of round 2 in what would be his final professional mixed martial arts bout to date.\n\n==Submission grappling==\nIn 2000, Hasdell was awarded his blackbelt in [[Ju Jutsu]] and personally invited by the Prince of [[Abu Dhabi]], [[United Arab Emirates]] to compete in the [[ADCC Submission Wrestling World Championship]] on 1 March 2000. Hasdell competed in the +99&nbsp;kg category and was eliminated by [[South Africa]]n Mark Robinson after the match went the distance.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://adcombat.com/adcc-events/adcc-2000-results/|title=Official Results|author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date= 1 March 2000|website=www.adcombat.com/|publisher= |access-date=4 April 2019 |quote='results.}}</ref> \n\nOn 21 January 2001, Hasdell won the Kamon European [[Brazilian Jujitsu]] tournament in London.<ref name=\"kamonwingchun.com\">{{cite web |url=http://www.kamonwingchun.com/Jiu-JitsuReportJan2001.asp |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2008-12-28 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061113054109/http://kamonwingchun.com/Jiu-JitsuReportJan2001.asp |archivedate=13 November 2006 |df=dmy-all }}. Retrieved 28 December 2008.</ref>\n\nOn 23 May 2009, Lee Hasdell took part in the U.M.A. International Open Groundfighting and Grappling Championships. Hasdell achieved Gold in the open weight masters division.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.umauk.co.uk/News.htm |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2009-06-30 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090622012000/http://www.umauk.co.uk/News.htm |archivedate=22 June 2009 |df=dmy-all }}. Retrieved 1 July 2009.</ref>\n\n==Promoting==\n===Total Fight Forum (RINGS UK)===\nIn 1997, Hasdell formed Universal Total-Fight Forum (U.T.F), later known as Total Fight Forum (T.F.F) in conjunction with [[Fighting Network RINGS|Rings]] and would later become President for Rings UK. On 5 October 1997 Hasdell promoted UTF's first professional event called 'Total Fight Night'. The show featured [[Vale Tudo]] and (Rings rules) [[shootfighting]] matches. On 8 March 1998, Hasdell promoted the first in a series of events called Night of the Samurai. The follow up Night of the Samurai II was held on 11 October 1998 and then Night of the Samurai III on 7 March 1999. Hasdell later promoted a fifth event called Total Fight KRG 5 on 3 October 1999.\n\nTotal Fight Forum featured international fighters from [[Japan]], [[United States]], [[Netherlands]], [[France]] and [[Spain]]. The events were held at the [[Sanctuary Music Arena]] and [[Planet Ice Milton Keynes|Planet Ice]] in [[Milton Keynes]], England. Hasdell also promoted many amateur Rings rules and Vale Tudo competitions between 1998 and 1999.<ref name=\"combudo1\">{{cite web |url=http://www.combudo.com/home-page |title=Executive Producer |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date= |website=Combudo |publisher= |access-date=18 August 2016 |quote= |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160902200901/http://www.combudo.com/home-page |archive-date=2 September 2016 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nIn 2000, Lee Hasdell promoted the Ring of Truth series,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sherdog.com/organizations/Ring-of-Truth-73|title=Ring of Truth |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date= |website= |publisher= |access-date=20 August 2016 |quote= }}</ref> these were three events featuring Vale Tudo and Rings king of kings bouts, it also featured a Ring of Truth Vale Tudo tournament.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://fightpics.tripod.com/events/ringoftruth.html |title=Ring of Truth Results |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date= |website= |publisher= |access-date=20 August 2016 |quote= }}</ref> These events were again held at the Sanctuary Music Arena in Milton Keynes.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.sherdog.com/news/articles/Anarchy-in-the-UK-34824|title=Anarchy in the U.K.|author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date= 22 August 2011|website=www.sherdog.com|publisher= |access-date=3 April 2019 |quote=Read more at https://www.sherdog.com/news/articles/Anarchy-in-the-UK-34824#imCZkcT75eXBWyfm.99.}}</ref> \n\nOn 9 June 2001, Hasdell staged a Grassroots competition featuring grappling, Thai boxing and Rings king of kings bouts.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sherdog.com/organizations/Hasdell-Competition-308|title=Hasdell Competition |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date= |website= |publisher= |access-date=20 August 2016 |quote= }}</ref>\n\nThese events produced and featured fighters such as James Zikic, [[Bobby Razak]], [[Paul Cahoon]], [[Gary Turner (fighter)|Gary Turner]], [[Ian Freeman]], [[Lee Murray]], [[Mark Weir]], [[Valentijn Overeem]], [[Wataru Sakata]], [[Hiromitsu Kanehara]], [[Yasuhito Namekawa]], [[Jess Liaudin]] and Danny Batten. \n\n====Criticism of MMA in the UK====\nThe events was the source of some criticism in the UK with critics arguing for an outright ban or better regulation of the events.<ref name=indep/> Hasdell responded to the complaints, arguing;\n\n{{Quote|\"In Japan you are seen as an athlete. [...] Here there is this taboo. It's always on the fringe. I admit it's dangerous but that adds to the thrill of taking part and watching. [...] The sport's appeal is the fact that it is the most dangerous martial art in this country which is a pull for audiences, half of which are women. [...] But all the fighters are properly trained, the rule book is 32 pages long, and there is not much contact to the head.<ref name=indep>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/life-style/health-and-wellbeing/health-news/doctors-want-ban-on-total-fighting-726526.html|title=Doctors want ban on 'total fighting'|date=6 February 2000|publisher=The Independent|first=Sophie|last=Goodchild|accessdate=4 January 2009}}</ref> Also all fighters must be a black belt in their martial art or a recognized champion\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.sherdog.com/news/articles/Anarchy-in-the-UK-34824|title=Anarchy in the U.K.|author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date= 22 August 2011|website=www.sherdog.com|publisher= |access-date=3 April 2019 |quote='all fighters must be a black belt in their martial art or a recognized champion.</ref>}} \n\nAfter relocating from the Sanctuary Music Arena to Planet Ice in Milton Keynes, Hasdell claimed;\n{{Quote|\u201cWe managed to sell 3,000 tickets. The council were watching and they realized that they can\u2019t stop this. Milton Keynes\u2019 council became the experts. They knew about the paramedics, the rules and the legal requirements. When other promoters started springing up around the U.K., all the councils went running to Milton Keynes and basically carbon copied all their documentation,\u201d<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.sherdog.com/news/articles/Anarchy-in-the-UK-34824|title=Anarchy in the U.K.|author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date= 22 August 2011|website=www.sherdog.com|publisher= |access-date=3 April 2019 |quote='\u201cWe managed to sell 3,000 tickets. The council were watching and they realized that they can\u2019t stop this. Milton Keynes\u2019 council became the experts. They knew about the paramedics, the rules and the legal requirements. When other promoters started springing up around the U.K., all the councils went running to Milton Keynes and basically carbon copied all their documentation,\u201d</ref>}} \n\nHasdell also insisted that the sport is adequately controlled<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/666647.stm|title=Doctors demand 'total fighting' ban |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date= 5 March 2000 |website= |publisher= |access-date=18 August 2016 |quote= But Lee Hasdell, the promoter of the Milton Keynes event, insists the sport is adequately controlled.}}</ref> and have an amazing safety record.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2000/feb/28/sarahhall|title=Opposition grows to new sport of total fighting |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date= 28 February 2000 |website= |publisher= |access-date=18 August 2016 |quote= But Lee Hasdell, the promoter of the Milton Keynes event, insists the sport is adequately controlled \"We have an amazing safety record. In 80 matches, not one person's had to spend a night in hospital.\"}}</ref>  Hasdell's events were featured on many News programs such as LWT Nightlife, [[Trevor McDonald]]'s ''[[Tonight (1999 TV programme)|Tonight]]'' programme on 22 July 1999 and also appeared on [[Johnny Vaughan]]'s ''[[The Big Breakfast]]'' show on 15 March 2000.\n\n===Combudo===\nLee Hasdell founded the Combudo organisation in 2000 and has staged many amateur events since. In 2008 he promoted a professional Combudo event featuring bouts under K-1, kickboxing and Thai boxing rules. The second professional event was held in 2009 and featured mixed martial arts matches.<ref name=\"combudo1\"/> Combudo specialises in modern Japanese Hybrid Budo Martial Arts and fuses together the ethics and spirituality of traditional budo with modern style self-defence and combat sports.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.combudo.com/home-page |title=Home page |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date= |website=Combudo |publisher= |access-date=18 August 2016 |quote= |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160902200901/http://www.combudo.com/home-page |archive-date=2 September 2016 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n===Other events===\nLee Hasdell promoted multiple amateur and professional Kickboxing events between 1993 and 1995. On 15 October 1995, Hasdell promoted Fighting Arts Gala in Milton Keynes. This event featured three shootfighting bouts on a mainly kickboxing stacked card, this event set the stage for his first official mixed martial arts event in 1997.\n\nIn 2002 and 2003, Hasdell promoted the UZI-Cage Combat Evolution series, a mixed martial arts and kickboxing event held in a Cage.<ref name=\"combudo1\"/>\n\nBetween 2009-2018, Lee Hasdell was the new and first [[ISKA]] UK National Director for MMA.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.iska.org.uk/news/article/iska_uk_launch_mma_division_headed_by_lee_hasdell/ |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2016-08-13 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303224050/http://www.iska.org.uk/news/article/iska_uk_launch_mma_division_headed_by_lee_hasdell/ |archivedate=3 March 2016 |df=dmy-all }}. Retrieved 16 December 2014.</ref> \n\nOn 9 March 2012, Hasdell took one of his students to compete at [[Fighting Network RINGS]]'s first official event in Japan for ten years.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.sherdog.com/news/news/Rings-Returns-with-March-9-Card-Featuring-K1-Max-Vet-Taishin-Kohiruimaki-40323|title=Rings Returns with March 9 Card Featuring K-1 Max Vet Taishin Kohiruimaki|author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date= 15 February 2012|website=www.sherdog.com|publisher= |access-date=3 April 2019 |quote='His opponent, Abbott, also comes from a kickboxing background and is a pupil of early Rings fighter Lee Hasdell.}}</ref> His student defeated [[K-1]] fighter [[Takayuki Kohiruimaki]] at [[List of Fighting Network Rings events|RINGS: Reincarnation]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.sherdog.com/events/Rings-Reincarnation-18638|title=Rings Reincarnation|author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date= 9 March 2012|website=www.sherdog.com|publisher= |access-date=3 April 2019 |quote='match result}}</ref> The following year, Hasdell took an amateur team to compete at the [[List of Fighting Network Rings events|RINGS: Rings/The Outsider]] event held on 9 June 2013.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://yanwutang.org/saishi/202.html|title=6\u67089\u65e5\u6a2a\u6ee8\u4e2d\u65e5\u683c\u6597\u4ea4\u6d41\u8d5b|last= |first= |date= 17 May 2013|access-date=3 April 2019 |language=Japanese|trans-title=June 9 Yokohama Sino-Japanese Fighting Exchange}}</ref> \n\nIn 2013 Hasdell became a consultant for the ISKA sanctioned 'KT-MMA' promotion.<ref>[http://www.mikethetruth.com/2013/11/kick-thai-mixed-martial-arts-k-t-mma-what/]. Retrieved 16 August 2016.</ref>\n\n==Championships and accomplishments==\n\n===Kickboxing===\n* [[World Kickboxing Association]] (WKA)\n** British super-middleweight (-76&nbsp;kg) [[kickboxing]] champion (1991)<ref name=totalfighter/>\n* British & International Kickboxing & Martial Arts Association (B.I.K.A)\n** British light-heavyweight (-79&nbsp;kg) [[Thai boxing]] champion (1991)<ref name=totalfighter/>\n** British light-heavyweight (-79&nbsp;kg) [[Kickboxing|free-style]] champion (1992)<ref name=totalfighter/>\n\n===Mixed martial arts===\n* [[Oktagon]]\n** world Oktagon champion (1996)<ref name=totalfighter/>\n* Universal Total-Fight Forum (U.T.F) / Total-Fight Forum (T.F.F)\n** super-fight heavyweight (90&nbsp;kg+) [[shootfighting]] champion (1997)<ref name=totalfighter/><ref name=\"kamonwingchun.com\"/>\n** super-fight heavyweight (95&nbsp;kg+) [[Vale Tudo]] champion (1998)<ref name=totalfighter/>\n\n===Submission grappling===\n* Kamon European [[Brazilian Jiu-Jitsu]] open winner (2001) [[File:Med 1.png|Gold]]<ref name=\"kamonwingchun.com\"/>\n* UMA 'No Gi' groundfighting championships (Men's masters division open-weight) winner (2009) [[File:Med 1.png|Gold]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.umauk.co.uk/UMA_Int_Open_May_2009_Results.txt |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2009-06-28 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150522001749/http://www.umauk.co.uk/UMA_Int_Open_May_2009_Results.txt |archivedate=22 May 2015 |df=dmy-all }}. Retrieved 28 December 2008.</ref>\n\n===Belts and honors===\n* [[Kickboxing]] (ISKA) \u2013 7th Dan Black Belt \n* Kickboxing (WKA) - Black Belt\n* [[Karate]] (BCKA/EKF) \u2013 7th Dan Black Belt \n* [[K\u016bd\u014d|Kudo Daido-Juku]] (KIF) \u2013 2nd Dan Black Belt \u2013 Master Azuma (2008)\n* [[Jujutsu]] (W.C.J.J.O) \u2013 Black Belt \n* Submission Arts Wrestling (SAW/AJJTF) \u2013 Black Belt  \u2013 Master Aso (2013)\n* Russian Ninja-Kan  - Black Belt (2019)\n* Combat Magazine Hall of Fame (1998)\n* Martial Arts Illustrated Magazine Hall of Fame (2015)\n<ref>[http://www.shinkarate.co.uk/instructors]. Retrieved 5 September 2019</ref><ref>[http://www.shinkarate.co.uk/kids-kickboxing]. Retrieved 1 August 2016</ref><ref>[http://www.15909.mrsite.com/page3.htm]. Retrieved 9 August 2016</ref>\n\n==Mixed martial arts record==\n* This [[mixed martial arts]] record includes the rules of; [[shootfighting]], Japanese hybrid - [[Fighting Network RINGS|RINGS King of Kings]] (KOK), [[wikt:no holds barred|no holds barred]] (NHB), [[Vale Tudo]], 'free-fight' [[shootboxing]] and [[Mixed martial arts rules|unified rules of MMA]].\n\n{{MMArecordbox\n| draws= 3\n| nc= 1\n| ko-wins= 9\n| ko-losses= 4\n| sub-wins= 5\n| sub-losses= 7\n| dec-wins= 1\n| dec-losses= 5\n| dq-wins= 1\n| dq-losses=\n| other-wins=\n| other-losses=\n}}\n\n===Mixed martial arts record===\n{{MMA record start}}\n|-\n| {{no2}}Loss\n| align=center| 16\u201316\u20133 (1)\n| Ivan Serati\n| Submission (rear naked choke)\n| [[2007 in Cage Rage Championships#Cage Rage 24|Cage Rage 24]]\n| {{dts|format=dmy|2007|December|1}}\n| align=center| 2\n| align=center| 1:34\n| [[London]], England\n|\n|-\n| {{no2}}Loss\n| align=center| 16\u201315\u20133 (1)\n| [[Mario Sperry]]\n| Submission (rear naked choke)\n| [[2007 in Cage Rage Championships#Cage Rage 22|Cage Rage 22]]\n| {{dts|format=dmy|2007|July|14}}\n| align=center| 1\n| align=center| 1:39\n| [[London]], England \n|\n|-\n| {{yes2}}Win\n| align=center| 16\u201314\u20133 (1)\n| Hiroyuki Ito\n| KO (Knee and punches)\n| Pain and Glory 2004\n| {{dts|format=dmy|2004|April|24}}\n| align=center| 1\n| align=center| 0:32\n| [[Birmingham]], England\n|\n|-\n| {{no2}}Loss\n| align=center| 15\u201314\u20133 (1)\n| [[Fedor Emelianenko]]\n| Submission (guillotine choke)\n| [[2001 in Fighting Network Rings#Rings: World Title Series 5